   "hider_text": "The wall breathes in slow pulses. Not with air, but with the weight of things not said. A crack runs through the plaster like a vein—dried sap, maybe, or old ink. You can feel it beneath your skin when you press your palm to the cold. It hums a frequency only you hear, faint as a sigh behind the door.  \n\nThe floorboards creak / The old garage door groans when it’s opened — not from rust, but from the way the hinges remember how to bend. There’s a scent of oil and damp metal, faint, like something that has waited too long to be touched. Outside, the grass is worn thin in patches where the wind has kept it down, and the air hums with the quiet of a summer evening that won / The wind doesn’t blow here — it *drags*. It pulls across the cracked earth like a hand that forgets how to rest, scraping at the edges of things. The sun doesn’t shine, it *presses*. It settles into the low ribs of the dunes, warm as breath against the back of your neck. You can feel the stone beneath your boots — not hard, not",
   "seeker_text": "The smell of rain on hot pavement.  \n\nNot the wet kind, not the cool kind. This is when the sun has baked the city into a slow, shimmering memory, and then the first drops hit—tiny, hesitant—like fingers tapping the skin of the world. It doesn’t soak in. It *sings*. A low, metallic hum, like old wires vibrating in the dark / The smell of wet pavement after rain.  \n\nNot the kind you get in cities with concrete and exhaust, but the kind that seeps through the cracks in old brick walls in a forgotten neighborhood—damp, earthy, alive. It clings to your shoes, your jeans, the back of your neck. You don’t know where it came from, only that when you step barefoot on / The smell of wet wool after rain.  \n\nNot the sharp, clean scent of new laundry, not the musty dampness of basement corners. This is the deep, earthy breath of a woolen coat left hanging in a garden shed on a gray afternoon. The kind that gathers in the corners of your awareness when you’re sitting still, when the wind stops and the world holds its breath."
  },
